Section A 

Pratik Raut's 2017 Pedals




It all had happened in late 2017 which led to the invention of these electronic and affordable video game or car racing pedals.

 

In 2017, once while I was using that asus's mouse as usual, the left click of it had started malfunctioning and later as time passed by, it had almost stopped working.





Due to the wonderful design of the mouse and out of curiosity, I had disassembled the mouse and had already acknowledged that the problem was due to the button of the mouse.

 

For verification, I then had quickly soldered two wires onto the two end points of the button respectively, after which the left click had started working after touching those ends of those two soldered wires manually to each other.

 

 


 

From this I had thought of creating the pedals controller using the asus mouse and then I had followed the same procedure for the right mouse button.

 

 

 

After finishing with the mouse part, I then had created a pedals layout model using cardboard and had taped the negative wire of these two buttons below the pedals followed by the positive wire of these two buttons that was taped at the center of the back side of these two pedals viz. the accelerator and the brake thereby covering the back side with aluminium foil respectively.

 

After this stage I then had glued cube shaped sponge beneath these two pedals respectively for getting a spring like effect and maintaining the ratio of the pedal press (most probably).

 

For a more twist, I then had attached a stick (which I had taken from the pool game) onto the middle button of the mouse using heat treatment for using it as a handbrake.

 

After finishing with the whole setup and with those test cases, I then had the last step of binding the keyboard's up arrow, down arrow and space key's key event to that of the mouse's left, right and middle buttons respectively.

 

My 2017 pedals worked flawlessly back then.

 

 

Pratik Raut's 2022 Pedals

 

 

Today, in 2022 I used the same approach that I had used in 2017 and altered and merged the resources of my previous model hereby creating an upgraded version of those pedals which I named it as Pratik Raut's 2022 pedals.

 

In this new version, as I wanted more realistic feeling of those pedals followed by the tough, solid and rigidness of the pedals layout, I used a wooden board for the base, two punching machines for the accelerator and brake not only for the spring like action but also for the proper housing of the physical structure of the wires.

 

 

For the mouse too, I have used an old android box's cabinet (cover) and kept it separate from the pedals for reachability which can later be connected to the pedals using clips.

 

Section B

Pratik Raut's Steering Wheel




 

The Typhoon 20100 steering wheel was purchased in 2010.

That steering wheel was working fine until 2018 when it had reached it's end of life due to failure of cable and circuit components.

 


 

It was an electrical steering wheel with rotation angle of 60but not until 2022.

 


 

Cause in 2022, I disassembled it and removed all the electrical components thereby converting it into a custom infinite degrees rotation angle mechanical steering wheel.

 

The reason behind this was for using the mobile's tilting sensitivity as the steering factor.

 

So, for mounting the mobile onto the steering wheel, at first, I had used the inside tray of VR headset by cutting the two sides of the lengthy tray for fitting it perfectly onto the steering wheel.

 

But later when I founded out my Cross's CT-CR01 stand that was designed for landscape devices I had purchased 8 years before in 2014, I quickly modified that one for a perfect grip and finally finalized that one as the mounting factor.

 

 

Getting Output

 

Pratik Raut's Pedals

 


 

While testing this new version, I encountered these two ways of getting the output from these pedals:

 

1. By binding keyboard's key events (2017)

2. By sending keyboard's key strokes (2022)

 

 


 

For executing the 2022 output method, I created a tool named 'Pedals' that would send the keys 'w' and 's' on every left and right click respectively as it's quite safer rather than binding the keys.

 

However, the result was quite as expected but it was with delays as so much to the point that it would almost have 1-4 seconds of delay between every left or right click respectively which would later cause performance issues and disturbance during gameplay.

 

I had already known this before creating the tool as of course there is a lot of difference between sending of keys and binding of keys especially in performance and response time.

 

Later some relative changes were done for boosting the performance making it equivalent to real time with addition to various options for suiting the needs of the game or app.

 

It has been tested on web game and works flawlessly whereas for other games usage of the key binding method for getting responsive output of the pedals in no time or real time is strongly recommended.




Here, by using the 2017 method, the keyboard keys are temporarily bound to the mouse using 'Glove PIE' application.

 

 



For steering wheel, the tilting sensitivity input is captured and received via 'Touch Racer' application.
